                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="17600534" author="emilles" created="Mon, 5 Sep 2022 23:52:28 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/apache/groovy/commit/75520486ccd7f12b4f4c1e93cba6e738eedd0aa7&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://github.com/apache/groovy/commit/75520486ccd7f12b4f4c1e93cba6e738eedd0aa7&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A method reference produces a &lt;tt&gt;MethodClosure&lt;/tt&gt; under plain STC, which supports reference to &lt;tt&gt;void&lt;/tt&gt; method adapted to value-bearing SAM (no runtime error; returns &lt;tt&gt;null&lt;/tt&gt;).  For that reason, I put the error check in the SC path.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17600843" author="chrylis" created="Tue, 6 Sep 2022 15:43:30 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I propose that even though in the case of STC/dynamic compilation there exists a chain of implicit transformations that can turn a void method into a &lt;tt&gt;Function&lt;/tt&gt;, this is virtually always a semantic error&#8212;no one feeding something to a &lt;tt&gt;map&lt;/tt&gt; or &lt;tt&gt;groupingBy&lt;/tt&gt; call expects the method reference to always return null. At a minimum, a warning seems appropriate, and I personally would still expect a compile-time error even if theoretically I can get there from here.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                    </comments>
